1
00:01:13,766 --> 00:01:14,849
MAN:
More blood.

2
00:01:15,476 --> 00:01:18,061
Great. Keep it coming.
Chuck, Terry, pump away.

3
00:01:18,395 --> 00:01:20,229
Don't be stingy.

4
00:01:20,397 --> 00:01:22,357
Okay, watch that arm.
I can see that fake arm.

5
00:01:22,524 --> 00:01:24,150
Chase, keep that claw really moving.

6
00:01:24,318 --> 00:01:27,195
Jeffrey, jam it on there just like
Freddy would. Good. Good.

7
00:01:27,363 --> 00:01:29,030
And cut. Print that, Gretchen.

8
00:01:29,239 --> 00:01:32,867
WOMAN:
Thank you, sir. Printing seven only.

9
00:01:34,286 --> 00:01:37,664
You're a genius. This makes his old claw
look like Mother Teresa's mitten.

10
00:01:37,831 --> 00:01:40,166
You better thank them,
they're very sensitive.

11
00:01:40,334 --> 00:01:43,252
-Chuck, Terry, great blood.
-Thank you very much.

12
00:01:43,420 --> 00:01:44,921
Some of our best work.

13
00:01:45,089 --> 00:01:46,798
Monkey man,
wanna see some neat stuff?

14
00:01:46,965 --> 00:01:47,965
-Yeah!
-Chase.

15
00:01:48,133 --> 00:01:49,759
Oh, come on.

16
00:01:49,968 --> 00:01:51,052
It's only make-believe.

17
00:01:51,762 --> 00:01:54,347
-Marianne, I gotta go.
-Okay.

18
00:01:54,515 --> 00:01:56,641
[CREW CHATTERlNG]

19
00:01:58,936 --> 00:02:00,561
Low bridge.

20
00:02:03,399 --> 00:02:07,527
We'll see if we can't find someone's
to scare the pj's off of Mommy.

21
00:02:10,114 --> 00:02:12,073
MAN:
Hey, Heather.

22
00:02:20,416 --> 00:02:22,250
You hungry, Dylan?

23
00:02:23,752 --> 00:02:25,336
[CHASE ROARS]

24
00:02:25,504 --> 00:02:26,796
[CHASE CHUCKLES]

25
00:02:28,257 --> 00:02:29,465
Ooh, gotcha.

26
00:02:29,633 --> 00:02:30,925
It should have flexed more.

27
00:02:31,093 --> 00:02:34,679
Chase, I think the servos
got shorted out with blood.

28
00:02:34,847 --> 00:02:39,767
Well, take it apart, pull it out,
and insulate them with some styro.

29
00:02:39,935 --> 00:02:42,979
Thing wasn't meant to be submerged,
for Pete's sake.

30
00:02:43,981 --> 00:02:45,022
I don't like that thing.

31
00:02:45,190 --> 00:02:46,733
It puts bread on our table.

32
00:02:46,900 --> 00:02:48,693
DYLAN:
Is it alive, Daddy?

33
00:02:48,861 --> 00:02:51,654
WOMAN:
Heather, you're in the next shot.

34
00:02:51,822 --> 00:02:54,907
State-of-the-art animatronics
enhanced with bio-organic grafting.

35
00:02:55,075 --> 00:02:56,159
Bull tendons.

36
00:02:56,326 --> 00:02:58,911
-Nerve bundles from a live Doberman.
-Chase.

37
00:03:04,418 --> 00:03:06,085
Whoa.

38
00:03:11,425 --> 00:03:13,176
Shit, Chuck!

39
00:03:13,886 --> 00:03:17,472
Uh, it must have picked up a signal
from an AD's walkie-talkie.

40
00:03:17,639 --> 00:03:19,515
TERRY: You sure it's turned off?
-It's off.

41
00:03:19,683 --> 00:03:22,935
It's funny, it's warm,
just like a real hand.

42
00:03:23,103 --> 00:03:24,103
[TERRY CHUCKLES]

43
00:03:25,189 --> 00:03:26,272
[HEATHER SCREAMS]

44
00:03:27,065 --> 00:03:28,733
Oh, God.

45
00:03:31,945 --> 00:03:34,197
What the hell is going on?
Cut the effects!

46
00:03:39,620 --> 00:03:40,953
HEATHER:
Chase!

47
00:03:41,121 --> 00:03:43,206
CHASE:
Terry, where is it?

48
00:03:43,373 --> 00:03:44,665
Terry!

49
00:03:44,833 --> 00:03:46,375
Chuck, get off me!

50
00:03:47,085 --> 00:03:48,127
Heather!

51
00:03:48,295 --> 00:03:50,671
-Heather, where is it?
TERRY: Chase, where the hell is it?

52
00:03:54,134 --> 00:03:55,301
Dylan!

53
00:03:55,469 --> 00:03:56,761
CHASE:
Come on!

54
00:03:56,929 --> 00:03:58,638
[TERRY GASPING]

55
00:04:00,307 --> 00:04:02,600
[SCREAMING]

56
00:04:03,977 --> 00:04:05,228
What the fuck?

57
00:04:10,234 --> 00:04:11,317
Dylan.

58
00:04:15,572 --> 00:04:17,865
Chase! No!

59
00:04:18,033 --> 00:04:19,075
[GASPING]

60
00:04:19,243 --> 00:04:20,660
CHASE:
Earthquake. Come on.

61
00:04:20,828 --> 00:04:22,829
[GLASS SHATTERING]

62
00:04:27,376 --> 00:04:29,085
DYLAN:
Mommy!

63
00:04:29,253 --> 00:04:30,586
HEATHER:
Dylan!

64
00:04:34,049 --> 00:04:36,092
Dylan! Dylan!

65
00:04:39,972 --> 00:04:41,264
Dylan!

66
00:04:47,896 --> 00:04:50,982
[CAR ALARMS WAILING]

67
00:04:51,608 --> 00:04:53,025
[SWINGS SQUEAKlNG]

68
00:05:01,118 --> 00:05:02,952
What is that?

69
00:05:03,120 --> 00:05:04,787
Car alarms.

70
00:05:08,458 --> 00:05:11,043
-You okay?
-Yeah.

71
00:05:12,796 --> 00:05:14,213
You okay, chief?

72
00:05:14,381 --> 00:05:15,882
-No.
CHASE: Heh, heh.

73
00:05:16,049 --> 00:05:18,676
-Honey, do you have a fever?
-Just another earthquake, Dylan.

74
00:05:18,844 --> 00:05:21,929
-Getting kind of fun, huh?
-Daddy, blood.

75
00:05:23,390 --> 00:05:25,141
CHASE:
It's nothing, guys.

76
00:05:25,309 --> 00:05:28,019
It's a scratch. Really.

77
00:05:28,186 --> 00:05:29,687
Where did you get that?

78
00:05:29,855 --> 00:05:33,274
I don't know. Picture, I guess.
The one that fell.

79
00:05:33,442 --> 00:05:34,734
It's no big deal.

80
00:05:34,902 --> 00:05:36,861
Put a bandage on it.

81
00:05:37,029 --> 00:05:38,946
Don't worry about it.

82
00:05:39,114 --> 00:05:41,490
[SIRENS APPROACHlNG]

83
00:05:41,658 --> 00:05:42,992
Whoo!

84
00:05:43,535 --> 00:05:45,328
[CHASE CHUCKLES]

85
00:05:46,663 --> 00:05:48,873
REPORTER [ON TV]:
Geologists at Caltech have confirmed...

86
00:05:49,041 --> 00:05:52,543
-...that this morning's aftershock....
-Do we have to watch that?

87
00:05:53,670 --> 00:05:56,589
CHASE: You turned it on.
-lt caused further collapse...

88
00:05:56,757 --> 00:05:59,008
...of the already badly damaged
parking structure....

89
00:05:59,384 --> 00:06:01,510
I'll turn it off.

90
00:06:01,678 --> 00:06:05,681
This is normal, following a quake
of last week's magnitude...

91
00:06:05,849 --> 00:06:08,559
...now thought to be a massive 6.8.

92
00:06:08,727 --> 00:06:09,852
[TV TURNS OFF]

93
00:06:10,729 --> 00:06:13,856
HEATHER: Dylan, this is breakfast,
not arts and crafts.

94
00:06:14,024 --> 00:06:15,107
CHASE:
Grr.

95
00:06:15,275 --> 00:06:16,776
What?

96
00:06:16,944 --> 00:06:18,819
Did you get any sleep last night?

97
00:06:18,987 --> 00:06:21,113
More or less.

98
00:06:21,281 --> 00:06:24,158
Okay, time to get dressed. I'm late.

99
00:06:24,326 --> 00:06:25,993
You're going away?

100
00:06:26,161 --> 00:06:29,372
Just for a few hours.
Julie will be with you.

101
00:06:34,628 --> 00:06:37,964
Is there anything other than the obvious
bothering you?

102
00:06:38,131 --> 00:06:41,550
I think five earthquakes in three weeks
is enough, sweetie.

103
00:06:42,886 --> 00:06:45,054
Hasn't been another phone call,
has there?

104
00:06:45,222 --> 00:06:46,555
No.

105
00:06:47,683 --> 00:06:50,935
Good sign. Two full weeks without him.

106
00:06:51,103 --> 00:06:52,311
Maybe he got hit by a truck.

107
00:06:52,896 --> 00:06:55,231
He's closer, if anything.

108
00:06:55,399 --> 00:06:57,650
It's giving me nightmares, Chase.

109
00:06:58,902 --> 00:07:00,194
Did you have one last night?

110
00:07:02,739 --> 00:07:04,991
Ah, it's just the earthquakes, Heather.

111
00:07:05,158 --> 00:07:06,742
Maybe.

112
00:07:07,411 --> 00:07:09,328
Maybe I shouldn't do
this interview today.

113
00:07:09,496 --> 00:07:14,458
No. You've gotta get back
on the horse sometime.

114
00:07:14,626 --> 00:07:17,670
Look, you had a nutcase
making harassing phone calls.

115
00:07:17,838 --> 00:07:22,091
-I know how scary that's been.
-No, you don't.

116
00:07:22,801 --> 00:07:25,970
Okay. I don't.

117
00:07:26,138 --> 00:07:28,556
But it doesn't mean
that it can't be over.

118
00:07:28,724 --> 00:07:31,350
Yeah, but what if it isn't over?

119
00:07:32,769 --> 00:07:35,855
Maybe you should tell me your dream.

120
00:07:36,606 --> 00:07:39,525
Oh, it was nothing. It was....

121
00:07:40,402 --> 00:07:42,945
You and I were working on this movie,
together for once...

122
00:07:43,113 --> 00:07:46,615
...and one of your special effects
went really wrong.

123
00:07:47,367 --> 00:07:51,328
And Chuck and Terry got hurt...

124
00:07:51,496 --> 00:07:55,833
...and, heh, well, your fingers were cut.

125
00:07:56,668 --> 00:07:58,169
Right here?

126
00:07:58,712 --> 00:07:59,754
Ooh!

127
00:08:00,797 --> 00:08:03,924
Heather, you were probably half-awake...

128
00:08:04,092 --> 00:08:07,762
...and saw my fingers get nicked
when the mirror fell. Dreams are like that.

129
00:08:12,142 --> 00:08:15,227
Look, if you don't want me
to go on this job, I won't.

130
00:08:17,773 --> 00:08:20,024
Pfft! Just be careful, okay?

131
00:08:20,567 --> 00:08:22,943
I think l can survive two days
in Palm Springs...

132
00:08:23,111 --> 00:08:25,821
...supplying soap bubbles
for a detergent commercial, don't you?

133
00:08:25,989 --> 00:08:27,156
I guess so.

134
00:08:27,324 --> 00:08:28,991
-You guess so?
-Yeah.

135
00:08:29,159 --> 00:08:30,534
Come here.

136
00:08:38,543 --> 00:08:42,671
Mmm. Forty eight hours.

137
00:08:43,465 --> 00:08:45,716
I'll be back in no time.

138
00:08:46,259 --> 00:08:48,636
-I gotta go.
-Okay.

139
00:08:50,847 --> 00:08:52,181
CHASE:
Hey!

140
00:08:56,603 --> 00:08:58,187
I love what you've done with the place.

141
00:09:00,023 --> 00:09:01,857
Knock them dead.

142
00:09:04,569 --> 00:09:07,196
Dylan, I gotta go! Take care of Mommy.

143
00:09:07,364 --> 00:09:08,364
DYLAN:
Bye.

144
00:09:08,532 --> 00:09:10,366
[RUMBLING]

145
00:09:17,582 --> 00:09:19,834
[CREAKlNG]

146
00:09:31,471 --> 00:09:33,556
TINA [ON TV]:
Nancy.

147
00:09:34,891 --> 00:09:36,350
Dylan.

148
00:09:37,477 --> 00:09:39,603
Nancy.

149
00:09:41,022 --> 00:09:43,440
Dylan, I don't want you watching this.

150
00:09:44,776 --> 00:09:47,486
[SCREAMING]

151
00:09:47,654 --> 00:09:50,322
What? What's wrong?
What's gotten into you?

152
00:09:53,034 --> 00:09:55,494
[PHONE RINGING]

153
00:10:04,963 --> 00:10:06,005
Hello?

154
00:10:06,173 --> 00:10:08,924
MAN [CHANTING]:
One, two--

155
00:10:11,928 --> 00:10:14,180
[PHONE RINGING]

156
00:10:21,605 --> 00:10:23,439
-Hello?
MAN: Freddy's coming for you!

157
00:10:27,485 --> 00:10:28,527
Chase!

158
00:10:28,695 --> 00:10:31,363
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING ON CAR RADIO]

159
00:10:38,038 --> 00:10:40,748
Someone's coming.

160
00:10:40,916 --> 00:10:42,124
What?

161
00:10:42,292 --> 00:10:44,585
[RUMBLING]

162
00:10:58,558 --> 00:11:01,101
-Are you okay, honey?
-Yes.

163
00:11:01,311 --> 00:11:03,062
[DOORBELL RINGS]

164
00:11:06,900 --> 00:11:07,942
JULIE:
Heather!

165
00:11:08,109 --> 00:11:10,027
[SIGHS]

166
00:11:14,658 --> 00:11:16,075
Hey.

167
00:11:17,494 --> 00:11:18,994
Is everything okay?

168
00:11:19,162 --> 00:11:21,997
Yeah. Just these quakes.
Did you feel a little one just now?

169
00:11:22,165 --> 00:11:24,500
Oh, no. A truck went by
right before you opened the door.

170
00:11:24,668 --> 00:11:26,669
That's life on the fault line.

171
00:11:26,836 --> 00:11:28,504
-Hey, tiger.
-Hi, Julie.

172
00:11:28,672 --> 00:11:30,172
Oh!

173
00:11:30,340 --> 00:11:34,176
Does he feel warm to you?
He had a fever this morning, I think.

174
00:11:34,344 --> 00:11:37,596
Hmm. No. He seems okay.

175
00:11:38,223 --> 00:11:40,266
Are you sure that's all that's wrong?
You seem--

176
00:11:40,433 --> 00:11:42,017
[PHONE RINGS]

177
00:11:43,186 --> 00:11:45,229
Leave us alone, you son of a bitch!

178
00:11:45,397 --> 00:11:47,189
DRIVER:
L.A. Limousine, ma'am.

179
00:11:47,357 --> 00:11:50,025
Just wanted you to know l'm out front.

180
00:11:56,908 --> 00:11:59,034
I'm sorry! Can you hang on a minute?

181
00:12:07,210 --> 00:12:08,585
Heather.

182
00:12:10,171 --> 00:12:13,716
-What is it?
-I don't know.

183
00:12:13,883 --> 00:12:15,843
I just have this weird feeling today.

184
00:12:16,011 --> 00:12:17,511
Mommy...

185
00:12:18,054 --> 00:12:20,681
-...stay home, then.
-Dylan.

186
00:12:26,229 --> 00:12:28,314
This damn caller.

187
00:12:30,233 --> 00:12:32,359
He started again?

188
00:12:33,361 --> 00:12:35,362
Sick fuck.

189
00:12:36,448 --> 00:12:38,115
Sorry.

190
00:12:39,284 --> 00:12:42,202
You know, Dylan doesn't
seem to have a fever.

191
00:12:42,370 --> 00:12:44,747
It's probably just your nerves.

192
00:12:44,914 --> 00:12:46,248
Nerves?

193
00:12:47,667 --> 00:12:50,336
I just meant from the shaker
this morning.

194
00:12:50,503 --> 00:12:53,130
I mean, everybody's freaked out
about how many we've been having.

195
00:12:53,298 --> 00:12:54,465
And then these phone calls.

196
00:12:54,632 --> 00:12:57,384
[PHONE RINGING]

197
00:12:59,387 --> 00:13:00,512
Don't answer it.

198
00:13:09,272 --> 00:13:11,273
-Hello?
DRIVER: Excuse me, ma'am...

199
00:13:11,441 --> 00:13:14,026
-...but we are going to be late.
-Okay.

200
00:13:16,321 --> 00:13:18,030
[FOOTSTEPS]

201
00:13:25,246 --> 00:13:26,830
Dylan?

202
00:13:26,998 --> 00:13:29,208
I gotta go. Forgive me?

203
00:13:29,918 --> 00:13:31,502
Bye.

204
00:13:45,225 --> 00:13:48,602
I'll, uh, call the cops for you.
You've got the number on the fridge, right?

205
00:13:48,770 --> 00:13:52,314
Just give them the time they called
and they're keeping this list, supposedly.

206
00:13:52,482 --> 00:13:54,316
Oh, Julie.

207
00:13:54,818 --> 00:13:56,902
I'm really sorry.
My nerves are a little raw.

208
00:13:57,070 --> 00:13:58,612
It's okay.

209
00:14:04,577 --> 00:14:05,702
[LAUGHS]

210
00:14:05,870 --> 00:14:07,246
Yeah. I gotta go.

211
00:14:07,414 --> 00:14:10,207
-Morning.
-Good morning.

212
00:14:24,848 --> 00:14:26,974
You play that girl?

213
00:14:27,517 --> 00:14:30,978
In that movie.
With the guy with the pfft!

214
00:14:32,355 --> 00:14:35,190
Yeah, sure. That's you.

215
00:14:36,317 --> 00:14:39,153
Ah, that's what I love about this job.
I get to meet the stars.

216
00:14:39,779 --> 00:14:41,321
I'm hardly a star.

217
00:14:41,489 --> 00:14:43,073
What? Are you kidding?

218
00:14:43,700 --> 00:14:46,243
I love your stuff.

219
00:14:46,536 --> 00:14:48,579
The first was the best.

220
00:14:48,746 --> 00:14:51,874
Your girlfriend's cut open
and dragged across the ceiling.

221
00:14:52,041 --> 00:14:53,041
It was awesome.

222
00:14:53,209 --> 00:14:55,752
When that blood comes out
of your boyfriend's bed?

223
00:14:55,920 --> 00:14:57,171
[DRIVER CHUCKLES]

224
00:14:57,338 --> 00:14:58,630
Yeah, I thought I'd shit.

225
00:14:58,798 --> 00:15:01,300
But they never should have
killed off Freddy!

226
00:15:02,552 --> 00:15:04,094
Heather, look, we gotta go! Let's go!

227
00:15:04,262 --> 00:15:07,514
Come on. Cutting it close, aren't you?
Trying to get me fired?

228
00:15:07,682 --> 00:15:09,558
Okay, okay, okay! We're coming!

229
00:15:09,726 --> 00:15:11,852
We're coming. No! No! No!

230
00:15:12,103 --> 00:15:15,063
So, Heather, we're approaching
the 1 0th anniversary...

231
00:15:15,231 --> 00:15:17,024
...of this Nightmare on Elm Street thing.

232
00:15:17,192 --> 00:15:20,319
I mean the original five
very popular sequels.

233
00:15:20,487 --> 00:15:25,324
How has all this success
affected you personally?

234
00:15:25,492 --> 00:15:28,869
Well, I don't know if it really has, Sam.
Oh, God.

235
00:15:29,037 --> 00:15:32,122
With the exception of 1 and 3,
I pretty much stayed out of it.

236
00:15:32,290 --> 00:15:34,541
You know, I'm doing a lot
more television now.

237
00:15:34,709 --> 00:15:37,503
Those hours let me spend more time
with my husband and my little boy.

238
00:15:37,670 --> 00:15:39,838
That's right, you have a little boy.
What's his name?

239
00:15:41,341 --> 00:15:42,633
Dylan.

240
00:15:42,800 --> 00:15:47,179
With Dylan, does that change your feeling,
your perspective about horror movies?

241
00:15:47,347 --> 00:15:48,931
No, not really.

242
00:15:49,098 --> 00:15:50,891
Would you let him see
one of your movies?

243
00:15:51,059 --> 00:15:53,185
My son? Heh, no.

244
00:15:53,353 --> 00:15:55,437
I'm sure people always ask you this
all the time.

245
00:15:55,605 --> 00:15:57,648
Is there going to be another sequel?

246
00:15:57,815 --> 00:16:01,568
And what's more, is Freddy really dead?

247
00:16:02,362 --> 00:16:04,321
Of course he is. Freddy's dead and gone.

248
00:16:04,489 --> 00:16:08,075
How about your co-star in the original,
in Nightmare 1 ?

249
00:16:08,243 --> 00:16:10,452
Would you trust him alone with Dylan?

250
00:16:10,870 --> 00:16:13,205
Robert? Heh. I don't know.

251
00:16:13,373 --> 00:16:15,624
Why don't we ask him
how he'd feel about it?

252
00:16:15,792 --> 00:16:19,127
We've got a big surprise for you,
Heather. And for our audience.

253
00:16:19,295 --> 00:16:21,713
Let's bring him out,
he is the best of the bad.

254
00:16:21,881 --> 00:16:24,049
Let's say hello to Robert Englund!

255
00:16:26,719 --> 00:16:29,096
[AUDIENCE CHEERING
AND APPLAUDlNG]

256
00:16:29,264 --> 00:16:32,224
["A NIGHTMARE ON ELM STREET"
THEME PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

257
00:16:32,392 --> 00:16:33,475
ROBERT:
Ha, ha!

258
00:16:33,643 --> 00:16:35,769
Love you, babe!

259
00:16:35,937 --> 00:16:38,063
We'll do lunch! Ha!

260
00:16:41,442 --> 00:16:44,236
All right! Yeah!

261
00:16:44,404 --> 00:16:47,614
Freddy's back!
Give it up for your Uncle Freddy!

262
00:16:49,826 --> 00:16:53,495
Just when you thought it was safe
to get back into bed!

263
00:16:53,663 --> 00:16:55,789
[LAUGHING]

264
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:58,041
Give me five!

265
00:17:02,505 --> 00:17:06,258
I'm back and I'm badder than ever!

266
00:17:06,426 --> 00:17:10,178
AUDIENCE [CHANTING]:
Freddy! Freddy! Freddy!

267
00:17:10,346 --> 00:17:14,850
ROBERT:
Ha! You are all my children now!

268
00:17:20,690 --> 00:17:24,568
-We've gotta go, Robert.
-Um, just a second. I'll walk you.

269
00:17:24,736 --> 00:17:26,778
-There you go, Christy.
GIRL: Thank you!

270
00:17:26,946 --> 00:17:28,947
ROBERT: Bye-bye!
GIRL: Thank you!

271
00:17:29,115 --> 00:17:31,158
-You okay?
-I'm fine.

272
00:17:31,326 --> 00:17:33,619
I don't know.
Everything went great, I thought.

273
00:17:33,786 --> 00:17:37,497
-We really got you, didn't we?
-I don't know why you didn't tell me.

274
00:17:37,665 --> 00:17:40,834
Come on, they loved
the expression on your face.

275
00:17:41,002 --> 00:17:44,463
-They'd like to see us together again.
-In what, a romantic comedy?

276
00:17:44,631 --> 00:17:49,009
Just because it's a love story doesn't mean
you can't have a decapitation or two.

277
00:17:49,177 --> 00:17:52,387
-Heather, there's a call for you.
-For me?

278
00:17:52,555 --> 00:17:55,599
-Listen, I'll talk to you later. Bye-bye.
-Bye-Bye.

279
00:17:55,767 --> 00:17:56,808
Hello?

280
00:17:56,976 --> 00:17:59,895
WOMAN: Heather, it's Sara Risher
over at New Line Cinema.

281
00:18:00,063 --> 00:18:01,188
How are you?

282
00:18:01,356 --> 00:18:03,982
Hi, Sara. How are you?
This is a voice from the past.

283
00:18:04,150 --> 00:18:07,235
lt sure is. Well, listen, Heather,
l won't take but a minute.

284
00:18:07,403 --> 00:18:09,655
lt's just that we have something
to propose to you...

285
00:18:09,822 --> 00:18:13,825
...and I wonder if you'd stop by the offices.
Bob would love to talk to you.

286
00:18:13,993 --> 00:18:15,077
Well, sure. When?

287
00:18:15,244 --> 00:18:17,579
No time like the present.
The car will bring you over.

288
00:18:17,747 --> 00:18:19,289
-Now?
-Just take a minute.

289
00:18:19,457 --> 00:18:22,334
You'll be glad you did, I bet. Bye.

290
00:18:46,859 --> 00:18:49,569
-Can I help you?
-I'm here to see Bob Shaye.

291
00:18:49,737 --> 00:18:51,071
Was Bob expecting you?

292
00:18:51,239 --> 00:18:54,366
-Heather? Hi.
-Sara, how are you?

293
00:18:54,534 --> 00:18:56,618
-I'm fine. How are you?
-Great to see you.

294
00:18:56,786 --> 00:18:58,161
-You look great.
-Thank you.

295
00:18:58,329 --> 00:19:00,038
Bob is dying to see you.

296
00:19:00,206 --> 00:19:02,666
-Can I get you something to drink?
-Coffee would be fine.

297
00:19:02,834 --> 00:19:04,126
-Black?
-Black's fine.

298
00:19:04,293 --> 00:19:05,669
Kim, could you get us some coffee?

299
00:19:05,837 --> 00:19:07,379
-Sure.
-Thanks.

300
00:19:07,547 --> 00:19:09,548
SHAYE:
I think the guy's a little bit of a jerk...

301
00:19:09,716 --> 00:19:11,717
...but we won't know
until we've read the script.

302
00:19:11,884 --> 00:19:15,762
Anyhow, l'll give you a call when l--
Hey! Listen, man, l gotta go.

303
00:19:15,930 --> 00:19:18,098
-Thanks.
SHAYE: Call me when you get to Milan.

304
00:19:18,266 --> 00:19:21,518
And don't forget, risotto con tartufo.
It's fantastico.

305
00:19:21,978 --> 00:19:23,854
Take care, man. I'll talk to you later. Bye.

306
00:19:25,022 --> 00:19:27,733
Boy, do you look great, Heather.
How are you?

307
00:19:27,900 --> 00:19:30,110
Great. I'm fine.

308
00:19:30,278 --> 00:19:32,529
I don't have to ask how you're doing.

309
00:19:32,697 --> 00:19:34,072
Well, so far, so good.

310
00:19:34,240 --> 00:19:36,950
Which, by the way,
is why we asked you to come by today.

311
00:19:37,618 --> 00:19:39,953
-Ah, thanks, Kim.
-Sure.

312
00:19:41,831 --> 00:19:43,790
Look, Heather,
let me cut to the chase.

313
00:19:43,958 --> 00:19:47,919
How would you like to join us
in the definitive Nightmare?

314
00:19:48,921 --> 00:19:51,173
I thought you killed Freddy off.

315
00:19:51,340 --> 00:19:54,176
Well, we did, but the fans--

316
00:19:54,343 --> 00:19:57,429
You know, the fans, God bless them,
they're clamoring for more.

317
00:19:57,597 --> 00:19:59,514
I guess evil never dies, right?

318
00:19:59,682 --> 00:20:01,600
Anyhow, a few weeks ago
I got a call from Wes...

319
00:20:01,768 --> 00:20:03,685
...and he pitched me
this really exciting idea.

320
00:20:03,853 --> 00:20:08,106
I started thinking, "Who better
to resurrect Freddy than his creator?"

321
00:20:08,691 --> 00:20:11,193
Well, I thought Wes stopped doing
horror movies.

322
00:20:11,360 --> 00:20:14,362
Do you know he actually told me
he hadn't called in the last 1 0 years...

323
00:20:14,530 --> 00:20:17,824
...because he hadn't had any
really scary nightmares.

324
00:20:17,992 --> 00:20:20,619
They're his inspiration for this thing.

325
00:20:20,787 --> 00:20:23,789
Anyhow, he's right
in the middle of the script.

326
00:20:24,499 --> 00:20:26,291
Which means he's having
nightmares again.

327
00:20:26,459 --> 00:20:28,126
Well, he's very excited about it.

328
00:20:28,294 --> 00:20:30,378
-The nightmares?
-No, sweetie, the script.

329
00:20:31,339 --> 00:20:35,175
And you should be too,
because you're the star.

330
00:20:37,053 --> 00:20:38,845
I don't know, Bob.

331
00:20:39,013 --> 00:20:41,723
I'm flattered, really.

332
00:20:42,225 --> 00:20:44,351
-But I have a kid now and--
-Well, so?

333
00:20:44,727 --> 00:20:47,562
So I'm not sure about doing horror.

334
00:20:47,730 --> 00:20:49,773
Oh, come on, Heather. Kids love horror.

335
00:20:51,943 --> 00:20:54,277
Thank you so much, Bob.

336
00:20:55,571 --> 00:20:56,863
I have other things happening.

337
00:20:57,031 --> 00:20:59,616
I promise you we'll match any offer
that's on the table.

338
00:20:59,784 --> 00:21:01,827
No. It's not that.

339
00:21:01,994 --> 00:21:03,161
Look, I have a fan.

340
00:21:03,329 --> 00:21:06,581
You've got plenty of fans. We've been
doing marketing research on you.

341
00:21:06,749 --> 00:21:09,125
You are rating right up there.

342
00:21:09,293 --> 00:21:11,586
We've got Chase working on
a prototype for the new glove.

343
00:21:11,754 --> 00:21:13,421
-It's really--
-What?

344
00:21:13,589 --> 00:21:16,299
Okay, I know, we asked him
to keep it as a surprise...

345
00:21:16,467 --> 00:21:19,803
...until you and I could
have this conversation.

346
00:21:20,388 --> 00:21:22,097
Bob...

347
00:21:23,349 --> 00:21:25,475
...how long has Wes
been working on this script?

348
00:21:26,435 --> 00:21:28,728
I don't know. A couple months. Why?

349
00:21:28,896 --> 00:21:31,940
Since you've been thinking of making it,
has anything funny happened?

350
00:21:33,192 --> 00:21:36,903
-What do you mean?
-Well, like weird phone calls?

351
00:21:37,071 --> 00:21:39,447
[PHONE RINGING]

352
00:21:42,285 --> 00:21:43,702
Or nightmares?

353
00:21:47,331 --> 00:21:49,040
Why don't you answer your phone, Bob?

354
00:21:49,959 --> 00:21:53,003
Come on. That's what we've got
people we pay around here for.

355
00:21:53,170 --> 00:21:55,672
Will someone pick up the damn phone?

356
00:22:11,480 --> 00:22:13,273
-Thanks a lot.
DRIVER: You're welcome.

357
00:22:13,441 --> 00:22:15,775
[DYLAN YELLING]

358
00:22:15,943 --> 00:22:17,027
Dylan?

359
00:22:26,454 --> 00:22:29,164
[DYLAN SCREAMING]

360
00:22:36,797 --> 00:22:40,884
[IN HOARSE VOICE]
Never sleep again.

361
00:22:41,052 --> 00:22:44,721
Never sleep again.

362
00:22:45,556 --> 00:22:47,557
[DYLAN SOBBING]

363
00:22:48,351 --> 00:22:49,809
What is going on?

364
00:22:49,977 --> 00:22:52,145
You didn't let him watch
the movie on TV, did you?

365
00:22:52,313 --> 00:22:55,899
Movie? He didn't watch anything on TV.

366
00:22:56,067 --> 00:22:58,860
He was taking his nap,
and I heard him screaming.

367
00:23:01,197 --> 00:23:02,864
Honey, are you okay?

368
00:23:03,032 --> 00:23:06,576
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Mm-hm. Rex saved me.

369
00:23:12,917 --> 00:23:14,709
He did?

370
00:23:20,508 --> 00:23:22,592
Is Rex going to die?

371
00:23:22,760 --> 00:23:24,552
No!

372
00:23:24,720 --> 00:23:26,680
Rex is not going to die.

373
00:23:26,847 --> 00:23:29,182
I promise you, sweetie.

374
00:23:32,353 --> 00:23:34,938
Do you know where the sewing stuff is
in the kitchen?

375
00:23:35,106 --> 00:23:36,690
Sure.

376
00:23:37,233 --> 00:23:40,527
We'll do an operation, okay? Come on.

377
00:23:40,695 --> 00:23:42,904
Dr. Dylan and Dr. Julie.

378
00:23:43,239 --> 00:23:47,075
Fix him up good as new, okay? Okay.

379
00:23:55,584 --> 00:23:59,587
MAN: Hey, Chase, you got a call!
It's your wife.

380
00:24:05,261 --> 00:24:09,055
-Heather.
-Chase, hi. You better come home.

381
00:24:09,223 --> 00:24:11,558
Oh, Heather, I'm stuck here.

382
00:24:11,726 --> 00:24:13,935
Neither Chuck or Terry came in today.

383
00:24:14,103 --> 00:24:15,520
Why? What's the matter?

384
00:24:15,688 --> 00:24:18,064
-Chase, it's Dylan.
-What?

385
00:24:18,232 --> 00:24:20,400
[STATIC HISSING OVER PHONE]

386
00:24:20,568 --> 00:24:22,444
Hold on. The phone's breaking up.

387
00:24:23,946 --> 00:24:27,782
Okay. What's going on with Dylan?

388
00:24:27,950 --> 00:24:31,536
He's had some sort of an episode.

389
00:24:31,704 --> 00:24:34,831
What? What kind of episode?

390
00:24:34,999 --> 00:24:38,209
He was just acting very strangely...

391
00:24:39,253 --> 00:24:40,920
...like somebody was after him.

392
00:24:41,088 --> 00:24:44,174
It's scary. It scared me.

393
00:24:44,800 --> 00:24:47,802
-He was acting like....
-Like what?

394
00:24:49,055 --> 00:24:50,555
Like Freddy.

395
00:24:52,016 --> 00:24:55,518
Heather, has there been
another phone call?

396
00:24:57,646 --> 00:25:00,899
Chase, why didn't you tell me
you were working on a new glove?

397
00:25:01,484 --> 00:25:03,318
And why aren't Chuck and Terry
at work today?

398
00:25:03,569 --> 00:25:05,570
Forget those clowns, Heather.
Answer me.

399
00:25:05,738 --> 00:25:07,697
Has there been another
phone call today or not?

400
00:25:10,993 --> 00:25:12,619
Yes.

401
00:25:14,371 --> 00:25:15,955
Okay.

402
00:25:16,123 --> 00:25:19,000
I'm coming home.
I'll be there in three hours.

403
00:25:22,004 --> 00:25:23,630
Danny, I gotta go.

404
00:25:23,798 --> 00:25:26,549
-What's up, Chase?
-My kid's sick. l gotta fly.

405
00:25:45,069 --> 00:25:46,694
HEATHER:
"As soon as the sun was up...

406
00:25:46,862 --> 00:25:49,197
...the witch made Gretel
fetch wood and kindle a fire.

407
00:25:49,365 --> 00:25:51,199
'We will bake cookies first,' she said.

408
00:25:51,367 --> 00:25:53,535
'I've heated the oven
and kneaded the dough.

409
00:25:53,702 --> 00:25:56,871
Crawl in and see if the fire
is blazing high enough now.'

410
00:25:57,039 --> 00:25:58,957
As she pushed Gretel
toward the oven...

411
00:25:59,125 --> 00:26:02,502
...the witch meant to shut the door
and bake her once she was inside."

412
00:26:02,670 --> 00:26:04,003
Dylan, this is so violent.

413
00:26:04,171 --> 00:26:07,799
I don't know why you like
these stupid old fairy tales.

414
00:26:07,967 --> 00:26:09,342
Finish, please.

415
00:26:09,510 --> 00:26:11,010
They're gonna give you nightmares.

416
00:26:11,178 --> 00:26:12,720
I like this story.

417
00:26:13,848 --> 00:26:15,014
[SIGHS]

418
00:26:16,142 --> 00:26:18,643
"But Gretel guessed
what the witch was planning.

419
00:26:18,811 --> 00:26:22,105
'I don't know how to get in,' Gretel said.
'How am I to manage it?'

420
00:26:22,273 --> 00:26:25,400
'Stupid girl,' shouted the witch
rushing up to the oven.

421
00:26:25,568 --> 00:26:28,736
'The opening is big enough.
See, I can fit myself.'

422
00:26:28,904 --> 00:26:32,073
Then quickly, Gretel came behind
and pushed with all her might...

423
00:26:32,241 --> 00:26:34,993
...plunging the wicked old woman
headlong into the flames...

424
00:26:35,161 --> 00:26:37,203
...banging the door shut
and bolting it tight.

425
00:26:37,371 --> 00:26:39,414
The witch howled."

426
00:26:40,166 --> 00:26:41,833
That's enough.

427
00:26:42,001 --> 00:26:44,043
"The witch howled like a scalded cat...

428
00:26:44,211 --> 00:26:47,380
...but Gretel ran and left her there
to perish nonetheless.

429
00:26:47,548 --> 00:26:50,258
She ran to her brother as fast as she could
and flung open the door.

430
00:26:50,426 --> 00:26:54,220
'Hansel! Hansel!' she cried,
'We're saved! The witch is dead!"'

431
00:26:58,267 --> 00:27:00,185
Time for sleep.

432
00:27:00,352 --> 00:27:01,978
Say how they find their way back home.

433
00:27:02,646 --> 00:27:03,730
Tomorrow night.

434
00:27:04,440 --> 00:27:05,773
No. Tonight.

435
00:27:06,275 --> 00:27:07,775
It's important.

436
00:27:11,113 --> 00:27:13,740
Dylan, you know as well as I do.

437
00:27:13,908 --> 00:27:16,284
They follow the trail of bread crumbs
back to their house.

438
00:27:16,452 --> 00:27:19,621
And then their father covered them
with kisses and they were safe.

439
00:27:20,247 --> 00:27:22,624
They were safe and they could sleep.
Now, come on.

440
00:27:26,629 --> 00:27:29,964
-What is that?
-Rex.

441
00:27:32,176 --> 00:27:33,676
Come on.

442
00:27:33,969 --> 00:27:35,720
[CHUCKLES]

443
00:27:40,351 --> 00:27:43,311
Rex keeps him down there.

444
00:27:43,687 --> 00:27:44,812
Who?

445
00:27:44,980 --> 00:27:47,232
The mean old man with the claws.

446
00:27:48,484 --> 00:27:50,318
He wants to come up
while we sleep.

447
00:27:51,237 --> 00:27:52,779
I keep my feet up here.

448
00:27:54,406 --> 00:27:56,574
Rex keeps him down there.

449
00:27:58,702 --> 00:28:00,161
He's my guard.

450
00:28:03,707 --> 00:28:05,708
You should have a guard too.

451
00:28:08,170 --> 00:28:11,798
Dylan, there's nothing down there.

452
00:28:11,966 --> 00:28:13,007
Come here.

453
00:28:15,302 --> 00:28:16,803
Look. See?

454
00:28:22,226 --> 00:28:25,144
It's different when you're gone.

455
00:28:25,938 --> 00:28:27,689
Come on.

456
00:28:39,743 --> 00:28:41,577
On, please.

457
00:28:41,745 --> 00:28:43,121
Okay, sweetie.

458
00:28:44,873 --> 00:28:46,541
[SIGHS]

459
00:28:46,709 --> 00:28:49,127
Night, night. Sleep tight.

460
00:28:49,503 --> 00:28:51,379
Don't let the bedbugs bite.

461
00:28:53,757 --> 00:28:55,550
Daddy coming home?

462
00:28:55,718 --> 00:28:57,093
He's on his way.

463
00:28:57,720 --> 00:28:59,637
DYLAN:
He can follow the bread crumbs, right?

464
00:29:00,097 --> 00:29:01,681
Right.

465
00:29:07,855 --> 00:29:11,441
If the birds don't eat them first.

466
00:29:13,402 --> 00:29:15,903
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING ON CAR RADIO]

467
00:29:24,079 --> 00:29:25,997
[TIRES SCREECHING]

468
00:29:38,552 --> 00:29:40,553
[DIALING PHONE]

469
00:29:44,099 --> 00:29:45,767
[STATIC CRACKLING OVER PHONE]

470
00:29:46,393 --> 00:29:50,104
Ah, perfect, perfect, perfect.

471
00:30:03,202 --> 00:30:06,120
[STATIC CRACKLING ON RADIO]

472
00:30:10,292 --> 00:30:12,126
[GROANS]

473
00:30:13,212 --> 00:30:16,798
Come on. Come on. Come on.

474
00:30:17,674 --> 00:30:21,302
[SINGING]
That's me in the corner

475
00:30:23,680 --> 00:30:28,393
That's me in the spotlight

476
00:30:28,560 --> 00:30:31,145
Light

477
00:30:31,313 --> 00:30:33,481
Losin' my

478
00:30:34,650 --> 00:30:36,734
Religion

479
00:30:48,622 --> 00:30:50,081
[SCREAMING]

480
00:30:52,668 --> 00:30:54,001
[TIRES SCREECHING]

481
00:30:56,338 --> 00:30:57,630
[GASPS]

482
00:31:00,968 --> 00:31:02,385
Mommy's scared?

483
00:31:03,804 --> 00:31:05,680
Dylan.

484
00:31:05,848 --> 00:31:08,015
Mommy's fine.

485
00:31:08,183 --> 00:31:10,726
It was just a bad dream.

486
00:31:10,894 --> 00:31:12,728
What are you doing out of bed?

487
00:31:12,896 --> 00:31:15,982
Rex woke me up. He was fighting.

488
00:31:16,150 --> 00:31:18,609
Dylan, go back to sleep, honey.

489
00:31:19,236 --> 00:31:20,987
I'm not sleepy.

490
00:31:21,613 --> 00:31:23,364
[DOORBELL RINGS]

491
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:34,041
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

492
00:31:34,209 --> 00:31:35,877
PATROLMAN:
Hello?

493
00:31:37,463 --> 00:31:40,339
Police, ma'am. Can you open the door?

494
00:31:53,562 --> 00:31:54,937
Heather Langenkamp?

495
00:31:55,898 --> 00:31:56,939
Yes?

496
00:31:57,441 --> 00:31:58,774
Is Chase Porter your husband?

497
00:32:01,111 --> 00:32:02,236
Yes.

498
00:32:02,404 --> 00:32:04,489
I'm afraid there was an accident.

499
00:32:04,656 --> 00:32:07,700
It appears he fell asleep
while driving, ma'am.

500
00:32:09,077 --> 00:32:12,079
Is he--? I mean--

501
00:32:12,247 --> 00:32:14,081
Is he hurt?

502
00:32:14,249 --> 00:32:17,001
I'm afraid it's worse than that, ma'am.

503
00:32:26,094 --> 00:32:27,970
Is he dead?

504
00:32:29,139 --> 00:32:30,223
Yes, ma'am.

505
00:32:35,604 --> 00:32:37,605
Are you sure it's him?

506
00:32:37,773 --> 00:32:40,942
We have his effects.
You can confirm from that.

507
00:32:42,945 --> 00:32:44,403
I wanna see his body.

508
00:32:45,572 --> 00:32:47,406
No, you don't, ma'am. lt's not necessary.

509
00:32:48,909 --> 00:32:51,786
I want to see it for myself.

510
00:32:55,874 --> 00:32:58,376
[WOMAN SOBBING
AND SHOUTING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

511
00:33:17,479 --> 00:33:20,439
[ELECTRIC SAW WHlRRING]

512
00:33:36,832 --> 00:33:38,833
[MEN CHATTERING]

513
00:33:40,335 --> 00:33:42,420
Ahem. Excuse me.

514
00:33:43,005 --> 00:33:45,881
-Can I help you?
-Porter.

515
00:33:46,049 --> 00:33:47,550
Chase Porter.

516
00:33:52,973 --> 00:33:56,100
It's back here.

517
00:34:03,400 --> 00:34:05,192
You said Chase?

518
00:34:05,360 --> 00:34:07,445
Mm-hm.

519
00:34:13,035 --> 00:34:14,785
I'm sorry.

520
00:34:24,046 --> 00:34:27,548
Just sign here at the bottom.
That's all we need.

521
00:34:28,925 --> 00:34:30,926
I'd like to see once again.

522
00:34:31,595 --> 00:34:32,803
I'm sorry?

523
00:34:32,971 --> 00:34:35,473
Could you lift the sheet again, please?

524
00:34:47,903 --> 00:34:48,903
More, please?

525
00:34:52,908 --> 00:34:53,949
What is that?

526
00:34:54,117 --> 00:34:55,951
It was a bad wreck, ma'am.

527
00:34:56,662 --> 00:35:00,206
The head's gonna be all right
for the funeral and all, but--

528
00:35:05,545 --> 00:35:07,046
Here, lady. You okay?

529
00:35:08,632 --> 00:35:11,175
-You sure?
-Yes.

530
00:35:11,343 --> 00:35:13,427
[SOBS]

531
00:35:17,057 --> 00:35:20,309
Oh, God. What did that?

532
00:35:20,477 --> 00:35:22,603
Well, they said the truck was tore up
something awful.

533
00:35:22,771 --> 00:35:25,272
So you can imagine him not being in...

534
00:35:26,024 --> 00:35:27,483
...well, exactly top shape.

535
00:35:28,694 --> 00:35:30,403
It looks like...

536
00:35:30,570 --> 00:35:32,029
...he was clawed.

537
00:35:33,740 --> 00:35:35,741
Yeah.

538
00:35:35,909 --> 00:35:38,244
Well, that's why
we don't lift the sheet...

539
00:35:38,412 --> 00:35:40,621
...past the face, ma'am.

540
00:35:42,416 --> 00:35:45,876
Sometimes it's what we don't see
that gets us through the night.

541
00:35:52,801 --> 00:35:56,303
So, uh, if you'll just sign....

542
00:36:03,395 --> 00:36:05,479
MINISTER:
God is our hope and strength...

543
00:36:06,481 --> 00:36:09,275
...a very present help in trouble.

544
00:36:09,443 --> 00:36:14,155
Therefore, we will not fear,
though the earth be moved...

545
00:36:14,322 --> 00:36:18,993
...and though the hills be carried
into the midst of the sea...

546
00:36:19,995 --> 00:36:23,122
...though the waters thereof
rage and swell...

547
00:36:23,290 --> 00:36:28,961
...and though the mountains shake
at the tempest of the same--

548
00:36:29,963 --> 00:36:31,881
[RUMBLING]

549
00:36:35,302 --> 00:36:37,303
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

550
00:36:46,563 --> 00:36:47,897
Look!

551
00:36:57,991 --> 00:36:59,867
[VOICES WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY]

552
00:37:04,206 --> 00:37:05,539
Julie, where's Dylan?

553
00:37:05,707 --> 00:37:07,583
I don't know.

554
00:37:09,544 --> 00:37:11,378
[CACKLING]

555
00:37:12,172 --> 00:37:15,216
Help! Mommy!

556
00:37:16,218 --> 00:37:17,802
Dylan!

557
00:37:20,180 --> 00:37:22,431
-Mommy!
HEATHER: Dylan!

558
00:37:22,599 --> 00:37:24,558
Dylan! Grab Mommy's hand!

559
00:37:24,726 --> 00:37:26,018
Grab it!

560
00:37:26,186 --> 00:37:27,728
Oh, my God!

561
00:37:29,397 --> 00:37:30,773
Hurry!

562
00:37:35,028 --> 00:37:36,779
[GASPING]

563
00:37:40,700 --> 00:37:41,951
Stay with me.

564
00:37:42,244 --> 00:37:43,786
Aah! No!

565
00:37:43,954 --> 00:37:45,246
Stay with me, Heather.

566
00:37:45,413 --> 00:37:46,831
No!

567
00:37:50,085 --> 00:37:53,629
-Where's Dylan? Where's Dylan?
-He's all right. He's right here.

568
00:37:57,592 --> 00:38:00,094
-Oh, what happened?
-It was an earthquake.

569
00:38:00,262 --> 00:38:02,012
You got knocked off your feet.

570
00:38:02,180 --> 00:38:04,723
You got a pretty good bump, actually.

571
00:38:05,016 --> 00:38:07,935
MINISTER:
May he rest in peace, children...

572
00:38:08,103 --> 00:38:10,855
...and may you all get home safely.

573
00:38:11,189 --> 00:38:12,940
ALL:
Amen.

574
00:38:18,280 --> 00:38:20,281
[SIRENS WAILING IN DISTANCE]

575
00:38:28,957 --> 00:38:31,834
If there's anything I can do, Heather.
Anything.

576
00:38:32,502 --> 00:38:34,712
Thank you, Robert.

577
00:39:00,655 --> 00:39:03,657
[MUSIC PLAYING ON TV]

578
00:39:16,421 --> 00:39:18,339
Sweetie?

579
00:39:23,053 --> 00:39:24,678
NANCY [ON TV]:
Tina?

580
00:39:27,515 --> 00:39:29,516
[MUMBLING INDISTINCTLY]

581
00:39:37,150 --> 00:39:38,192
Dylan.

582
00:39:45,158 --> 00:39:46,758
Tina?

583
00:39:52,749 --> 00:39:54,583
Who are you?

584
00:39:59,714 --> 00:40:02,174
[FREDDY CACKLING ON TV]

585
00:40:07,847 --> 00:40:10,057
Dylan.

586
00:40:10,225 --> 00:40:11,308
Baby, wake up.

587
00:40:11,476 --> 00:40:12,726
[SCREAMS]

588
00:40:12,894 --> 00:40:16,355
Dylan! Dylan! Dylan, honey.

589
00:40:16,523 --> 00:40:19,066
Shh, shh, shh.

590
00:40:19,234 --> 00:40:20,943
Come on.

591
00:40:21,111 --> 00:40:23,237
Okay, sugar.
We're gonna go back to bed now.

592
00:40:23,405 --> 00:40:25,614
No, Mommy, I can't sleep there.

593
00:40:26,241 --> 00:40:28,575
Honey, you have to sleep.

594
00:40:29,202 --> 00:40:34,748
[CHANTlNG]
One, two, Freddy's coming for you

595
00:40:34,916 --> 00:40:38,419
Where did you hear that?
Did you hear that on that movie?

596
00:40:39,254 --> 00:40:40,462
Did you answer the phone?

597
00:40:42,048 --> 00:40:44,675
Dylan, where did you hear that song?

598
00:40:44,926 --> 00:40:46,760
In my bed.

599
00:40:48,596 --> 00:40:50,097
In your bed?

600
00:40:50,598 --> 00:40:53,475
Under my covers. Kids singing.

601
00:40:54,019 --> 00:40:56,687
And way down there, the man...

602
00:40:56,980 --> 00:40:59,481
...the mean man....

603
00:41:02,694 --> 00:41:04,278
What is that man doing?

604
00:41:04,779 --> 00:41:06,739
Trying to get up.

605
00:41:06,906 --> 00:41:09,700
Trying to get up into our world.

606
00:41:12,871 --> 00:41:14,621
Dylan.

607
00:41:40,815 --> 00:41:43,484
Where is Daddy now?

608
00:41:49,115 --> 00:41:51,533
Daddy's in heaven.

609
00:41:52,869 --> 00:41:55,329
He's with God now.

610
00:41:57,707 --> 00:42:01,752
Do you have to die to see God?

611
00:42:02,420 --> 00:42:04,505
I don't think so.

612
00:42:07,467 --> 00:42:09,760
I think you have to pray.

613
00:42:11,888 --> 00:42:13,430
And reach out.

614
00:42:18,686 --> 00:42:21,605
Why does God let there be bad things?

615
00:42:25,610 --> 00:42:28,237
I honestly don't know, honey.

616
00:42:30,907 --> 00:42:33,492
Please try to get some sleep.

617
00:42:40,083 --> 00:42:41,750
[SIGHS]

618
00:42:42,961 --> 00:42:45,212
Can you come with me in my dreams?

619
00:42:50,426 --> 00:42:53,512
I think that only happens in the movies.

620
00:42:55,098 --> 00:43:00,978
But I'll always, always,
be right here when you get back.

621
00:43:02,772 --> 00:43:04,439
And I'll make sure...

622
00:43:04,607 --> 00:43:09,069
...that nobody gets your toes.

623
00:43:36,764 --> 00:43:39,141
[CHILDREN CHATTERING]

624
00:43:58,453 --> 00:44:01,496
HEATHER:
I know his behavior is bizarre.

625
00:44:01,664 --> 00:44:03,957
But he's usually so normal
and well adjusted, John.

626
00:44:04,125 --> 00:44:08,795
I just can't believe it's him
and not something outside influencing him.

627
00:44:09,797 --> 00:44:12,424
Or is that how denial works?

628
00:44:12,884 --> 00:44:16,720
Whether it is denial,
I don't think that's the case here.

629
00:44:16,888 --> 00:44:20,432
Look, if you're really worried about Dylan,
have a doctor check him out.

630
00:44:20,600 --> 00:44:21,975
You'll see. Everything's fine.

631
00:44:22,977 --> 00:44:25,812
You're not just saying that
to help a crazy friend cope, are you?

632
00:44:25,980 --> 00:44:27,648
[SIGHS]

633
00:44:27,815 --> 00:44:30,692
Everything about Dylan's behavior
is understandable...

634
00:44:30,860 --> 00:44:33,820
...for a kid who just lost his father.

635
00:44:33,988 --> 00:44:37,199
How does a child process
a thing like that?

636
00:44:37,951 --> 00:44:39,910
I don't know.

637
00:44:41,120 --> 00:44:43,288
I've not been able to process it
very well myself.

638
00:44:44,082 --> 00:44:46,124
And you're not crazy, by the way.

639
00:44:46,584 --> 00:44:49,670
Seeing Freddy in that grave
feels pretty crazy, and then jumping in.

640
00:44:50,171 --> 00:44:52,506
-You didn't jump in.
-That's my memory.

641
00:44:52,674 --> 00:44:54,216
It seemed absolutely real.

642
00:44:54,384 --> 00:44:57,177
Seemed, not was.

643
00:44:57,512 --> 00:44:58,845
[SIGHS]

644
00:44:59,013 --> 00:45:00,180
It's....

645
00:45:00,348 --> 00:45:01,682
It's in my family, you know.

646
00:45:02,225 --> 00:45:03,809
What is?

647
00:45:03,977 --> 00:45:06,853
A very close relative
died in an institution.

648
00:45:07,021 --> 00:45:12,067
Really? Well, if having a screwy family
made a person crazy...

649
00:45:12,235 --> 00:45:15,862
...the whole world would be
one big loony bin.

650
00:45:17,699 --> 00:45:20,200
You have a crazed fan after you.

651
00:45:20,368 --> 00:45:23,370
That's what's making you crazy,
and probably Dylan too.

652
00:45:23,997 --> 00:45:25,914
-I never mentioned that to him.
-Kids know.

653
00:45:26,082 --> 00:45:29,209
Kids know when something's
bugging a parent.

654
00:45:30,169 --> 00:45:33,130
You have no idea who this is calling?

655
00:45:33,298 --> 00:45:34,631
Freddy, for all I know.

656
00:45:34,799 --> 00:45:35,841
Come on.

657
00:45:36,843 --> 00:45:39,219
It's a man...

658
00:45:39,387 --> 00:45:42,973
...or a boy, with a deep, you know...

659
00:45:43,141 --> 00:45:44,182
...Freddy voice.

660
00:45:44,350 --> 00:45:48,228
Six weeks of this, and you're surprised
you've got Freddy in your dreams?

661
00:45:48,396 --> 00:45:50,105
Hell, Sonny Bono...

662
00:45:50,273 --> 00:45:53,358
...after a while began seeing
his stalker everywhere, even at Mass.

663
00:45:53,526 --> 00:45:55,110
HEATHER:
Really?

664
00:45:56,571 --> 00:45:59,865
JOHN: And how many times did Letterman
call the cops thinking that woman...

665
00:46:00,033 --> 00:46:02,200
-...was down in the kitchen again?
-Yeah.

666
00:46:02,577 --> 00:46:06,246
I mean, it gets under your skin if you....
If you let it.

667
00:46:09,208 --> 00:46:10,250
[GRUNTS]

668
00:46:11,210 --> 00:46:13,170
You really think Dylan's okay?

669
00:46:13,338 --> 00:46:16,423
Dylan's fine. You're fine.

670
00:46:16,591 --> 00:46:20,052
You're hurting but you're fine,
and you're definitely not crazy.

671
00:46:21,137 --> 00:46:23,347
My worst fear...

672
00:46:23,514 --> 00:46:26,975
...that whatever madness
is in my family I have.

673
00:46:37,153 --> 00:46:40,072
That I've passed it on to Dylan.

674
00:46:49,290 --> 00:46:50,624
HEATHER:
Dylan!

675
00:46:50,792 --> 00:46:52,667
[DYLAN SCREAMING]

676
00:46:56,714 --> 00:46:57,964
-Heather!
HEATHER: Dylan!

677
00:46:58,132 --> 00:47:00,842
-Make sure he's okay, John!
-Yeah, are you all right?

678
00:47:01,010 --> 00:47:02,594
-Are you okay, huh?
HEATHER: Oh, my God.

679
00:47:02,762 --> 00:47:06,640
-Are you sure? Does anything hurt?
-Dylan, are you all right? Honey?

680
00:47:06,808 --> 00:47:08,767
Are you all right? Are you sure?

681
00:47:09,310 --> 00:47:11,228
God wouldn't take me.

682
00:47:14,190 --> 00:47:15,982
Oh, my God. Oh, honey.

683
00:47:16,150 --> 00:47:17,567
JOHN:
It's unbelievable.

684
00:47:58,860 --> 00:47:59,901
[SIGHS]

685
00:48:05,825 --> 00:48:08,368
[PHONE RINGING]

686
00:48:14,041 --> 00:48:15,500
-Yeah.
-Robert.

687
00:48:16,461 --> 00:48:18,712
-Heather, you doing all right?
-Hanging in there.

688
00:48:18,880 --> 00:48:20,839
You know the guy that was
calling me all the time?

689
00:48:21,007 --> 00:48:24,342
He started again.
And he's putting stuff in my mail again.

690
00:48:24,510 --> 00:48:28,221
The SOB probably read about the funeral
in the papers or something.

691
00:48:28,723 --> 00:48:33,226
Sick mother. It's the last thing
you need right now, I'm sure.

692
00:48:33,394 --> 00:48:36,730
Actually, it's been giving me
Freddy nightmares.

693
00:48:36,898 --> 00:48:39,274
Wait a second,
now let me get this straight.

694
00:48:39,442 --> 00:48:41,902
You're having nightmares about Freddy?

695
00:48:42,069 --> 00:48:43,111
As in me?

696
00:48:43,279 --> 00:48:47,365
No, it isn't you. He's scarier.

697
00:48:49,577 --> 00:48:51,077
He's....

698
00:48:51,245 --> 00:48:54,456
Darker? More evil?

699
00:48:55,416 --> 00:48:57,667
Yeah. How did you know?

700
00:48:58,586 --> 00:48:59,711
Call it a guess.

701
00:49:00,379 --> 00:49:02,923
Pretty damn good guess.

702
00:49:03,090 --> 00:49:05,550
Anyway, what I was calling about was...

703
00:49:05,718 --> 00:49:07,761
...have you seen any of the script
by any chance?

704
00:49:08,804 --> 00:49:13,141
No. Wes won't show it until he's finished.
At least that's what he told me.

705
00:49:13,309 --> 00:49:14,768
Well, when is it gonna be done?

706
00:49:14,936 --> 00:49:19,981
Well, the way he's writing, who knows?
He's so weird.

707
00:49:20,149 --> 00:49:23,068
I asked him how far he was
at the funeral. What did he say?

708
00:49:23,236 --> 00:49:27,364
Oh, yeah. "As far as Dylan
trying to reach God."

709
00:49:27,532 --> 00:49:30,283
Whatever that means. Weird, huh?

710
00:49:30,868 --> 00:49:33,078
Putting your kid in the script.

711
00:49:33,579 --> 00:49:38,124
Robert, have you been
having nightmares?

712
00:49:41,587 --> 00:49:43,964
Look, we need to talk,
but not over the phone.

713
00:49:44,131 --> 00:49:46,299
Can I come over?

714
00:49:46,467 --> 00:49:50,178
Um, actually, Heather, uh...

715
00:49:50,555 --> 00:49:52,931
...today's no good. There's, um....

716
00:49:53,099 --> 00:49:56,643
There's something I have to finish.
Tomorrow maybe, huh?

717
00:49:57,478 --> 00:50:00,146
Okay, tomorrow.
But early in the morning.

718
00:50:00,314 --> 00:50:03,525
And meanwhile, Robert, take care, okay?

719
00:50:03,693 --> 00:50:06,319
Yeah. Sure.

720
00:50:06,487 --> 00:50:07,654
[PHONE BEEPS]

721
00:50:22,753 --> 00:50:24,879
[CREAKlNG]

722
00:50:27,425 --> 00:50:28,633
[MOANING]

723
00:50:48,529 --> 00:50:51,129
[CREAKlNG CONTlNUES]

724
00:52:20,746 --> 00:52:22,038
[SCREAMS]

725
00:52:31,799 --> 00:52:32,841
Damn it!

726
00:52:33,008 --> 00:52:34,467
[GRUNTING]

727
00:52:48,315 --> 00:52:53,695
DYLAN [CHANTING]:
One, two, Freddy's coming for you

728
00:52:55,364 --> 00:52:56,964
Dylan?

729
00:53:02,955 --> 00:53:07,125
DYLAN:
Three, four, better lock your door

730
00:53:11,380 --> 00:53:15,592
Five, six, grab your crucifix

731
00:53:18,763 --> 00:53:23,183
Seven, eight, better stay up late

732
00:53:24,518 --> 00:53:27,437
Dylan. Don't sing that song.

733
00:53:29,482 --> 00:53:34,152
Nine, 1 0, never sleep again

734
00:53:37,031 --> 00:53:38,406
Dylan!

735
00:53:38,574 --> 00:53:39,949
Stop it!

736
00:53:40,701 --> 00:53:41,826
No!

737
00:53:41,994 --> 00:53:43,161
[SCREAMS]

738
00:53:43,704 --> 00:53:44,913
[GLASS SHATTERS]

739
00:53:46,332 --> 00:53:48,458
DYLAN [CHANTING]:
Never sleep again

740
00:53:48,959 --> 00:53:51,559
Never sleep again

741
00:54:24,912 --> 00:54:25,912
Dylan.

742
00:54:26,080 --> 00:54:31,543
Never sleep again

743
00:54:31,710 --> 00:54:33,419
Never sleep ag--

744
00:54:33,587 --> 00:54:35,672
[PHONE RINGS]

745
00:54:37,591 --> 00:54:40,051
-Yes.
FREDDY: Ha-ha-ha. I touched him.

746
00:54:40,761 --> 00:54:42,720
[SCREAMING]

747
00:54:45,391 --> 00:54:47,392
[DYLAN SHRIEKING]

748
00:55:09,373 --> 00:55:11,958
Any history of epilepsy in your family?

749
00:55:12,126 --> 00:55:13,209
HEATHER:
No.

750
00:55:13,377 --> 00:55:15,962
HEFFNER: Diabetes?
-No.

751
00:55:16,130 --> 00:55:17,672
Was there a trigger event?

752
00:55:17,840 --> 00:55:20,216
Trauma, shock?

753
00:55:20,759 --> 00:55:23,636
You haven't shown him any of the films
you've made, have you?

754
00:55:23,804 --> 00:55:25,638
The horror stuff?

755
00:55:25,806 --> 00:55:28,016
His father just passed away.

756
00:55:28,684 --> 00:55:30,184
HEFFNER:
I'm sorry.

757
00:55:31,312 --> 00:55:32,478
But I'm convinced...

758
00:55:32,646 --> 00:55:37,525
...those films can tip an unstable child
over the edge.

759
00:55:37,693 --> 00:55:39,485
Unstable?

760
00:55:39,653 --> 00:55:42,989
Dylan's not unstable. He's just upset.

761
00:55:43,157 --> 00:55:45,658
HEFFNER: We'll run tests
and we'll know in a few days.

762
00:55:46,285 --> 00:55:48,119
Does he have to stay here overnight?

763
00:55:48,287 --> 00:55:50,163
Absolutely.

764
00:55:53,751 --> 00:55:56,085
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
Dr. Degraffey, ER.

765
00:55:56,253 --> 00:55:59,505
Anything more happen
we need to know about?

766
00:56:00,925 --> 00:56:01,966
Well, like what?

767
00:56:02,843 --> 00:56:06,554
Sometimes what a child says
or fantasizes...

768
00:56:06,722 --> 00:56:08,848
...will give a clue to what ails him.

769
00:56:09,850 --> 00:56:12,602
Did he say anything
while he was still lucid?

770
00:56:19,693 --> 00:56:20,777
No.

771
00:56:27,368 --> 00:56:29,494
Dr. Einhorn, line 237.

772
00:56:29,662 --> 00:56:31,579
What do we have here?

773
00:56:31,747 --> 00:56:33,873
Too soon to know for sure.

774
00:56:34,041 --> 00:56:36,960
The early symptoms point
to childhood schizophrenia.

775
00:56:41,382 --> 00:56:44,217
Dylan, can you hear me?

776
00:56:46,095 --> 00:56:48,221
Dylan, you have to fight it...

777
00:56:48,389 --> 00:56:51,599
...whatever it is that's after you,
and you gotta come back to me.

778
00:56:51,767 --> 00:56:54,519
You can't make it alone. Do you hear?

779
00:56:57,731 --> 00:57:01,651
If you can hear me, then you can tell me
what you need to feel safe.

780
00:57:08,325 --> 00:57:10,368
Rex? Is that what you want?

781
00:57:12,913 --> 00:57:15,707
Well.... Well, Rex is at home...

782
00:57:15,874 --> 00:57:18,376
...and that's where you should be.

783
00:57:18,544 --> 00:57:21,212
But you gotta get better
before they'll let you come home.

784
00:57:21,380 --> 00:57:22,547
Do you understand?

785
00:57:24,717 --> 00:57:26,050
Home.

786
00:57:26,218 --> 00:57:28,928
Home. Home, that's right.

787
00:57:29,096 --> 00:57:31,264
That's where I want you, sweetie.

788
00:57:31,432 --> 00:57:34,183
And you know, we're not that far away.

789
00:57:34,351 --> 00:57:37,311
Look. Look, right out there...

790
00:57:37,479 --> 00:57:40,732
...past the freeway is our home.

791
00:57:40,941 --> 00:57:42,191
But to get there...

792
00:57:43,318 --> 00:57:45,778
...you have to come out
from where you are...

793
00:57:46,488 --> 00:57:49,824
...so that they'll let you
come home to Rex...

794
00:57:49,992 --> 00:57:51,576
...and to me.

795
00:57:53,120 --> 00:57:54,537
Time for your medicine, cowboy.

796
00:57:57,458 --> 00:57:58,791
HEATHER:
What is that?

797
00:57:58,959 --> 00:58:00,877
Something to help him sleep.

798
00:58:01,503 --> 00:58:02,545
Okay.

799
00:58:04,631 --> 00:58:08,301
There you go. Yeah, it's good.

800
00:58:13,307 --> 00:58:15,141
There you go.

801
00:58:16,435 --> 00:58:18,686
One, two, good.

802
00:58:18,854 --> 00:58:20,605
Good! Attaboy!

803
00:58:20,773 --> 00:58:22,774
Come on, now lie down
and take a little nap.

804
00:58:22,941 --> 00:58:25,568
You should get some rest too.
He's going to be fine.

805
00:58:25,736 --> 00:58:29,280
We're gonna do some tests
and then you can come back later.

806
00:58:29,865 --> 00:58:32,158
Will you get that other side, please?

807
00:58:32,785 --> 00:58:34,577
I grabbed his things.

808
00:58:34,745 --> 00:58:37,580
These are his favorite pajamas here.

809
00:58:38,749 --> 00:58:39,999
Um....

810
00:58:40,584 --> 00:58:42,376
Honey, I've gotta go.

811
00:58:42,544 --> 00:58:44,670
I love you, Dylan.

812
00:58:44,880 --> 00:58:47,048
Remember what I said.

813
00:58:48,592 --> 00:58:50,676
We'll take care of everything.

814
00:58:57,226 --> 00:58:58,518
Bye.

815
00:59:39,726 --> 00:59:41,394
[HORN HONKS]

816
00:59:45,023 --> 00:59:47,066
MAN:
Wake up, lady!

817
00:59:49,736 --> 00:59:51,904
Don't lose it now!

818
01:00:07,796 --> 01:00:10,173
WOMAN [ON RADIO]:
Seismologists at Caltech have counted...

819
01:00:10,340 --> 01:00:12,133
...over 300 of the tremblers so far.

820
01:00:12,301 --> 01:00:14,427
Though most were too faint
for us to feel...

821
01:00:14,595 --> 01:00:17,263
...seven have shaken our community
in the last two weeks.

822
01:00:17,431 --> 01:00:20,766
And now scientists are speculating
there might be an unknown fault...

823
01:00:20,934 --> 01:00:23,102
...running beneath Los Angeles.
A fault that could--

824
01:00:23,270 --> 01:00:24,312
[TURNS RADIO OFF]

825
01:00:32,613 --> 01:00:33,863
[LlNE RlNGING]

826
01:00:34,031 --> 01:00:36,616
ROBERT [ON MACHINE]:
Hi. You've reached the Englund residence.

827
01:00:36,783 --> 01:00:38,201
We're out of town right now.

828
01:00:38,368 --> 01:00:43,539
You can leave a message if you wish,
but, uh, we'll be gone for some time.

829
01:01:07,648 --> 01:01:11,067
WES: I wish l could tell you where this
script was going. The fact is l don't know.

830
01:01:11,235 --> 01:01:15,404
You know, I dream a scene at night.
I write it in the morning.

831
01:01:15,572 --> 01:01:18,032
Beyond that, your guess is as good
as mine where it's going.

832
01:01:18,200 --> 01:01:20,326
Well, at least tell me
what it's about so far.

833
01:01:22,412 --> 01:01:24,497
-Coffee.
-Thanks.

834
01:01:24,665 --> 01:01:26,832
I can tell you
what the nightmare's about so far.

835
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:31,003
It's about this entity,
whatever you want to call it.

836
01:01:31,171 --> 01:01:33,839
It's old. It's very old.

837
01:01:34,508 --> 01:01:37,677
It's existed in different forms
in different times.

838
01:01:37,844 --> 01:01:40,388
The only thing that stays the same
is what it lives for.

839
01:01:40,555 --> 01:01:42,431
What is that?

840
01:01:42,599 --> 01:01:45,059
Well, the murder of innocence.

841
01:01:46,061 --> 01:01:49,897
This is still a script
we're talking about, right, Wes?

842
01:01:50,691 --> 01:01:54,735
Yeah, well, I sort of think of it
as a nightmare in progress.

843
01:01:55,028 --> 01:01:58,656
Well, in this nightmare in progress then,
does this thing have any weaknesses?

844
01:01:58,824 --> 01:02:00,825
Well, it can be captured sometimes.

845
01:02:00,993 --> 01:02:03,160
Captured? How?

846
01:02:03,328 --> 01:02:05,288
By storytellers, of all things.

847
01:02:06,373 --> 01:02:10,626
I mean, every so often they imagine a story
good enough to sort of catch its essence...

848
01:02:10,794 --> 01:02:14,297
...and then for a while
it's held prisoner in the story.

849
01:02:14,464 --> 01:02:18,467
-Like the genie in the bottle.
-Exactly. Exactly.

850
01:02:18,927 --> 01:02:20,845
But the problem comes
when the story dies.

851
01:02:21,013 --> 01:02:22,430
That can happen in a lot of ways.

852
01:02:22,597 --> 01:02:24,390
It can get too familiar to people...

853
01:02:24,558 --> 01:02:26,892
...or somebody waters it down
to make it an easier sell.

854
01:02:27,060 --> 01:02:31,564
You know, or maybe it's just so upsetting
to society that it's banned outright.

855
01:02:31,898 --> 01:02:35,359
However it happens when the story dies,
the evil is set free.

856
01:02:36,570 --> 01:02:40,531
You're saying
Freddy is this ancient thing?

857
01:02:40,699 --> 01:02:43,534
Right. Current version.

858
01:02:43,702 --> 01:02:46,412
And for 1 0 years,
he's been held captive pretty much...

859
01:02:46,580 --> 01:02:50,041
...as Freddy in the
Nightmare on Elm Street series...

860
01:02:50,208 --> 01:02:52,460
...but now that the films have ended...

861
01:02:52,753 --> 01:02:54,420
...the genie's out of the bottle, Heather.

862
01:02:54,588 --> 01:02:58,382
That's what the nightmares are telling me
and that's what I'm writing.

863
01:02:58,550 --> 01:03:01,177
Well, if Freddy is loose in your script...

864
01:03:01,928 --> 01:03:03,220
...where's he gonna go?

865
01:03:03,388 --> 01:03:05,973
Another age? Another form?

866
01:03:06,141 --> 01:03:09,101
No. That's not what the dreams
have him doing though.

867
01:03:09,561 --> 01:03:11,604
What is he doing?

868
01:03:12,189 --> 01:03:14,440
Well, see, he's sort of gotten
used to being Freddy now...

869
01:03:14,608 --> 01:03:19,445
...and he likes our time and space,
so he's decided to cross over.

870
01:03:19,613 --> 01:03:21,781
Out of films, into our reality.

871
01:03:26,244 --> 01:03:28,245
Isn't there somebody
who can stop him?

872
01:03:29,664 --> 01:03:31,791
Actually, there is a person
in the dreams...

873
01:03:31,958 --> 01:03:35,294
...sort of a gatekeeper, so to speak.

874
01:03:35,837 --> 01:03:40,257
Somebody that Freddy has to get by
before he can come through into our world.

875
01:03:41,676 --> 01:03:43,010
That person's you, Heather.

876
01:03:43,178 --> 01:03:45,971
-It's me?
-Yeah.

877
01:03:46,390 --> 01:03:47,598
But why me?

878
01:03:47,766 --> 01:03:50,309
Well, dramatically speaking,
it makes perfect sense.

879
01:03:50,477 --> 01:03:51,977
You played Nancy, after all.

880
01:03:52,145 --> 01:03:54,146
You were the first to humiliate him,
defeat him.

881
01:03:54,314 --> 01:03:57,108
That was Nancy, Wes, it's not me.

882
01:03:57,275 --> 01:04:00,111
Yeah, but it was you
that gave Nancy her strength...

883
01:04:00,278 --> 01:04:03,322
...so in order to get out
he's got to come through you.

884
01:04:03,490 --> 01:04:07,576
And it's inevitable that he's gonna try
to do that at your most vulnerable points.

885
01:04:09,579 --> 01:04:14,458
Oh, my God, Wes. Did you know?

886
01:04:15,794 --> 01:04:17,336
Heather, it was a script.

887
01:04:18,130 --> 01:04:20,840
It was a dream. I didn't know.

888
01:04:21,591 --> 01:04:24,760
You know damn well
it's more than that now.

889
01:04:25,011 --> 01:04:28,931
Wes.

890
01:04:29,099 --> 01:04:30,433
How can we stop him?

891
01:04:32,352 --> 01:04:35,438
I think the only way to stop him
is to make another movie.

892
01:04:36,731 --> 01:04:39,817
I swear I'll stay by this computer
and write until I finish the script...

893
01:04:39,985 --> 01:04:44,321
...but when that time comes,
you're gonna have to make a choice.

894
01:04:44,489 --> 01:04:47,491
Choice? What kind of choice?

895
01:04:47,659 --> 01:04:50,786
Whether or not you're willing
to play Nancy one last time.

896
01:05:17,564 --> 01:05:20,232
HEATHER: "Many of the symptoms
of childhood schizophrenia...

897
01:05:20,400 --> 01:05:25,237
...are duplicated in children
suffering from sleep deprivation."

898
01:05:31,411 --> 01:05:34,914
"Sleep deprivation can produce
trance-like states...

899
01:05:35,081 --> 01:05:36,582
...mechanical behavior...."

900
01:05:36,750 --> 01:05:38,626
DYLAN:
I'm not sleepy.

901
01:05:38,793 --> 01:05:40,544
Rex woke me up.

902
01:05:40,712 --> 01:05:43,756
He was fighting the mean old man
with the claws.

903
01:05:43,924 --> 01:05:46,342
You have no idea who this is calling?

904
01:05:46,510 --> 01:05:47,760
Freddy, for all I know.

905
01:05:47,928 --> 01:05:49,053
As in me?

906
01:05:49,221 --> 01:05:51,847
HEATHER:
No, it isn't you. He's scarier.

907
01:05:52,015 --> 01:05:54,600
-Darker? More evil?
-How did you know?

908
01:05:54,768 --> 01:05:56,477
WES:
He's decided to cross over...

909
01:05:56,645 --> 01:05:58,896
...out of films, into our reality.

910
01:05:59,064 --> 01:06:02,483
[IN HOARSE VOICE]
Never sleep again.

911
01:06:15,080 --> 01:06:18,249
The world of horror films
suffered its own terror today...

912
01:06:18,416 --> 01:06:21,627
...as two of Hollywood's best-known
special-effects technicians...

913
01:06:21,795 --> 01:06:24,213
...were found dead in a vacant field.

914
01:06:24,381 --> 01:06:26,590
Terrance Feinstein
and Charles Wilson...

915
01:06:26,758 --> 01:06:30,636
...two special-effects artists reputedly
working on a top-secret project...

916
01:06:30,804 --> 01:06:33,180
...for the makers of
the Freddy Krueger films...

917
01:06:33,348 --> 01:06:36,892
...were found brutally slashed to death
early this morning.

918
01:06:45,986 --> 01:06:49,863
Freddy's glove was missing, and police are
speculating the murders were the result...

919
01:06:50,031 --> 01:06:51,156
[RUMBLING]

920
01:06:51,324 --> 01:06:54,326
...of a botched theft,
which apparently took place two days ago.

921
01:06:54,494 --> 01:06:57,621
At this point the murder weapon
has not been found--

922
01:06:59,249 --> 01:07:00,332
[GASPS]

923
01:07:02,002 --> 01:07:04,169
[SCREAMING]

924
01:07:14,347 --> 01:07:16,682
[CREAKlNG]

925
01:07:34,034 --> 01:07:36,201
Oh, God.

926
01:07:56,973 --> 01:07:58,390
[CREAKlNG]

927
01:08:00,769 --> 01:08:01,810
Miss me?

928
01:08:01,978 --> 01:08:04,104
[SCREAMING]

929
01:08:19,162 --> 01:08:20,412
[FREDDY GRUNTS]

930
01:08:28,546 --> 01:08:29,880
Nancy.

931
01:08:31,591 --> 01:08:33,300
[RUMBLING]

932
01:08:49,776 --> 01:08:53,195
Ow!

933
01:08:56,533 --> 01:08:58,075
Oh, Dylan. Dylan!

934
01:08:58,326 --> 01:09:01,203
NURSE: There are no visiting hours.
You must understand.

935
01:09:01,371 --> 01:09:04,665
JULIE:
No, I don't understand. I'm his babysitter.

936
01:09:04,833 --> 01:09:08,836
I'm a close friend of the family, damn it.
I just need to see him for a minute.

937
01:09:09,003 --> 01:09:11,547
-Sixty seconds. Come on.
-You have to understand...

938
01:09:11,715 --> 01:09:14,133
-...I can't let you see him.
-Julie?

939
01:09:14,634 --> 01:09:16,844
-Heather.
-What are you doing here?

940
01:09:19,013 --> 01:09:20,639
I don't know.

941
01:09:21,641 --> 01:09:23,684
I had this terrible dream about Dylan.

942
01:09:24,644 --> 01:09:26,145
I had to come and see him.

943
01:09:27,814 --> 01:09:28,939
You must think I'm crazy.

944
01:09:30,191 --> 01:09:33,110
No, I don't. Is he all right?

945
01:09:33,278 --> 01:09:35,112
I don't know, they wouldn't let me in.

946
01:09:35,280 --> 01:09:38,657
Miss Langenkamp, I'm afraid
there are no evening visiting hours...

947
01:09:38,825 --> 01:09:40,659
-...in intensive care.
-Is he all right?

948
01:09:40,827 --> 01:09:43,120
Dylan? He's holding well.

949
01:09:43,663 --> 01:09:45,289
Earlier, he had some problems.

950
01:09:45,457 --> 01:09:47,291
He's in an oxygen tent just now.

951
01:09:47,459 --> 01:09:48,709
Oh, my God.

952
01:09:48,877 --> 01:09:50,669
Heather.

953
01:09:51,296 --> 01:09:54,006
Seems we've had an accident,
Miss Langenkamp.

954
01:09:54,174 --> 01:09:55,632
May I?

955
01:09:57,218 --> 01:10:00,804
Those are nasty cuts.
How did you get them?

956
01:10:00,972 --> 01:10:03,599
It happened in the earthquake.

957
01:10:04,017 --> 01:10:05,350
I fell.

958
01:10:05,518 --> 01:10:06,935
I need to see Dylan.

959
01:10:07,103 --> 01:10:11,023
Wait a moment.
First, let's see about you.

960
01:10:14,986 --> 01:10:18,363
HEFFNER: lf these had been
a few inches nearer the wrist....

961
01:10:19,115 --> 01:10:21,200
What did you say you cut yourself on?

962
01:10:21,367 --> 01:10:23,744
It was the earthquake, it was dark,
I have no idea.

963
01:10:24,829 --> 01:10:26,622
But these look quite fresh.

964
01:10:26,790 --> 01:10:30,125
They are.
It happened in tonight's earthquake.

965
01:10:31,419 --> 01:10:34,338
It happened just 1 5 minutes ago.

966
01:10:34,714 --> 01:10:35,756
You must have felt it.

967
01:10:38,718 --> 01:10:40,511
Guess we lucked out over here.

968
01:10:43,097 --> 01:10:48,352
Your son is apparently
terrified of a man...

969
01:10:48,520 --> 01:10:51,814
...someone he thinks is going
to come out of his bed.

970
01:10:52,273 --> 01:10:55,400
One of the nurses heard him
talking to himself.

971
01:10:56,361 --> 01:10:58,737
Do you have any idea
who that man is, Miss Langenkamp?

972
01:11:00,365 --> 01:11:02,241
I forgot to bring his dinosaur, Rex.

973
01:11:02,408 --> 01:11:05,828
He keeps Freddy
from coming up out of his...

974
01:11:07,455 --> 01:11:08,539
...bed.

975
01:11:08,706 --> 01:11:11,250
The man from your films?

976
01:11:12,085 --> 01:11:15,295
Freddy Krueger? With the claws?

977
01:11:17,006 --> 01:11:18,465
Is that who he's afraid of?

978
01:11:24,347 --> 01:11:27,349
You have let your child
see your films, haven't you?

979
01:11:27,517 --> 01:11:29,935
Every kid knows who Freddy is.

980
01:11:30,103 --> 01:11:33,772
He's like Santa Claus or King Kong or....

981
01:11:34,566 --> 01:11:37,776
Yes. Well...

982
01:11:37,944 --> 01:11:40,571
...interesting talking with you,
Miss Langenkamp.

983
01:11:42,156 --> 01:11:43,365
I hope you understand.

984
01:11:43,533 --> 01:11:46,493
My concerns are simply
for the welfare of your son.

985
01:11:52,667 --> 01:11:54,918
[EKG BEEPING]

986
01:12:02,010 --> 01:12:03,093
[FOOTSTEPS]

987
01:12:08,433 --> 01:12:09,975
How's he doing?

988
01:12:17,442 --> 01:12:18,567
[HEATHER SIGHS]

989
01:12:44,469 --> 01:12:46,261
[EKG FLATLINING]

990
01:12:52,477 --> 01:12:53,518
Dylan!

991
01:12:55,229 --> 01:12:58,315
Honey! You shouldn't do that.

992
01:12:58,483 --> 01:13:00,192
[IN HOARSE VOICE]
Too late.

993
01:13:00,902 --> 01:13:05,030
I'm almost there, Heather.

994
01:13:05,198 --> 01:13:07,699
[IN DEEP VOICE]
Almost there!

995
01:13:09,285 --> 01:13:10,535
[SCREAMING]

996
01:13:13,456 --> 01:13:14,790
Daddy!

997
01:13:15,166 --> 01:13:16,208
Dylan!

998
01:13:16,376 --> 01:13:17,584
-Help!
DYLAN: Daddy!

999
01:13:21,047 --> 01:13:22,756
[DYLAN GRUNTING]

1000
01:13:24,509 --> 01:13:25,676
Doctor!

1001
01:13:25,843 --> 01:13:26,927
Keep her right there!

1002
01:13:27,095 --> 01:13:28,971
NURSE:
We can't hold him much longer, doctor.

1003
01:13:29,138 --> 01:13:32,140
-Full anesthetic. Stat!
-We don't have that here, doctor.

1004
01:13:32,892 --> 01:13:36,144
No anesthetic, you say.
Screw it then, I'm going in.

1005
01:13:36,312 --> 01:13:38,563
Little booger's full of something
I don't like.

1006
01:13:38,731 --> 01:13:40,482
Let's get him open.

1007
01:13:40,650 --> 01:13:42,317
Cut this evil out of him.

1008
01:13:43,653 --> 01:13:44,695
Ha!

1009
